author: geomanis
body:
Hey friend, I've worked a lot with akamai cdn / prolexic / bot defender / kona products. Can say the following:

1. enterprise contracts super expensive compared to peers
2. quality of support is lacking, their soc and oncall network eng are ex accenture/infy/tata consultancy (automod hates them) and it shows. have a real problem retaining talent
3. waf uncompelling, signal sciences / sqreen for iast products better than kona and imperva is pure play better waf product. the cheap aws / azure / cloudflare wafs based on modsec are arguably better too
4. bot defender gets wrecked by Kasada and PerimeterX just no comparison
5. cdn product still best in breed if you're a legacy enterprise who cant hire any site reliability engineers or software engineers. this is mainly government agencies and banks who want to pay engineers 60k instead of 140k and wonder why they cant attract talent.

I dont think id use Akamai again, regardless of the number of golf trips theyd take me on.

Company is just getting its marketshare eaten by pure play vendors (sqreen, signla science, imperva) or cloud everything (cloudflare, aws, azure) and sits in the middle being expensive and bad. 😔

author: erniekim
body:
This won't materialize soon.  Given my experience worked at Accenture, this just means that PLTR is going to make an investment to start training IBM to sell their product.  Not too many people at IBM know what PLTR has and how they can sell them.  So this is how it goes

\- Phase 1: PLTR is going to start educating IBM partners what they have and how it can help them achieve numbers

\- Phase 2: PLTR and IBM then have to identify few target clients that could be a pilot for both to work on 

\- Phase 3: 2-3 pilot programs and success stories that will generate $xx million in sales for IBM and then blast to the whole IBM communities so other partners become interested

\- Phase 4: IBM then will build internal capabilities to sell PLTR solutions and start hiring and training people to become proficient at designing and implementing PLTR-driven solutions

\- Phase: Scale

&#x200B;

This will take 5-7 years for something massive to happen.  The same way it took Accenture, IBM and all other tech-driven consulting companies to start selling Salesforce products/solutions.

author: geomanis
body:
Hey friend, I've worked a lot with akamai cdn / prolexic / bot defender / kona products. Can say the following:

1. enterprise contracts super expensive compared to peers
2. quality of support is lacking, their soc and oncall network eng are ex accenture/infy/tata consultancy (automod hates them) and it shows. have a real problem retaining talent
3. waf uncompelling, signal sciences / sqreen for iast products better than kona and imperva is pure play better waf product. the cheap aws / azure / cloudflare wafs based on modsec are arguably better too
4. bot defender gets wrecked by Kasada and PerimeterX just no comparison
5. cdn product still best in breed if you're a legacy enterprise who cant hire any site reliability engineers or software engineers. this is mainly government agencies and banks who want to pay engineers 60k instead of 140k and wonder why they cant attract talent.

I dont think id use Akamai again, regardless of the number of golf trips theyd take me on.

Company is just getting its marketshare eaten by pure play vendors (sqreen, signla science, imperva) or cloud everything (cloudflare, aws, azure) and sits in the middle being expensive and bad. 😔

author: erniekim
body:
This won't materialize soon.  Given my experience worked at Accenture, this just means that PLTR is going to make an investment to start training IBM to sell their product.  Not too many people at IBM know what PLTR has and how they can sell them.  So this is how it goes

\- Phase 1: PLTR is going to start educating IBM partners what they have and how it can help them achieve numbers

\- Phase 2: PLTR and IBM then have to identify few target clients that could be a pilot for both to work on 

\- Phase 3: 2-3 pilot programs and success stories that will generate $xx million in sales for IBM and then blast to the whole IBM communities so other partners become interested

\- Phase 4: IBM then will build internal capabilities to sell PLTR solutions and start hiring and training people to become proficient at designing and implementing PLTR-driven solutions

\- Phase: Scale

&#x200B;

This will take 5-7 years for something massive to happen.  The same way it took Accenture, IBM and all other tech-driven consulting companies to start selling Salesforce products/solutions.

author: sonofalando
body:
Been eyeing ACN. Info tech company out of Ireland who had a massive quarter 8 PE up from 4 quarters around the 1 range . On a bearish pattern right now after hitting ATH, but just acquired new technology org. Tits deep many areas of infotech and utilities. Not a ton of debt, costs as much as GME, and has been above the 200SMA YOY. Only 600m outstanding shares, not much short float, 74% institutional ownership. Seems like it could be a value play though entry is a bit spendy. Downside is debt taken on acquiring said company, but could also offer future upside.

Went on a bearish trend for a day and now seems to have entered a sideways volatile pattern with support in the 240 range. 

Thoughts from anyone else? Seems like a good value play. What am I missing?

author: Wkingwest
body: Nokia has:  Positives -  No debt 90,000+ employees 5G contracts in EU Has a lead on 6G R&D in EU Makes chipsets for most major brand networking switches (Cisco) Retains 20K patents on various telco technologies Has won a $14 million contract with NASA to set up communications infrastructure in the moon (who knows where this could lead if successful - beyond the MOON?) In 1964, their research department discovered cosmic microwave background radiation - they have the resources to discover other interesting endeavors They are transparent in their business dealings, partnerships, and current/upcoming projects, they will also start releasing quarterly financial reports as well Outside of China, they own 27% of the world's telco infrastructure Moving to cloud services like storage and software (SaaS) Internet of Things in the Healthcare industry My 3310 from the year 2000 is still running and has not needed to be plugged in to charge yet  Negatives -  They have lost out on their contract with the 5G rollout in China. They were only involved in phase one, but did not win a tender to participate in phase two. Only Ericsson and Huawei won that round  I think it is a decent long term stock. And at $4.7 - $5 a stock, it is nothing to lose sleep over. They are not gonna go out of business, and you are not going to get wiped out. If it can only go up, then that's a good thing, short term or long term.**Show less**

author: graiz
body:
I've been long on NET since it's IPO and have been a customer of cloudflare for many years before this. 

I'm long for two reasons.   
\#1 - They have the best technology. They focus on low-level network technology like DNS and for years they have had the best technology, best performance and IMO the best price for the value. This makes it a no-brainer for most high-traffic websites.  It's easy to sell the best product and their sales are growing accordingly. 

\#2 - They are constantly innovating.  They keep pushing the state of the art and performance across a number of areas.  CDN, DNS, Smart Routing, Analytics, etc. These products work really well together and they scale with the speed of the Internet. Most people don't know about Cloudflare or their tech so I think they have a ton of room for growth and market expansion. 

Compare NET with older network companies like Cisco, Oracle, EMC, and others.  There's a ton of room for growth and many older companies that don't have the best technology and aren't quick to innovate. 

NET, NET. I like this stock a lot.

author: brentis
body:
Cloudflare has effectively taken much of the AWS stack and compressed it into a single deployment.   Back in the day when you could deploy to one server in datacenter was simple, but didn't scale.  Then you had AWS with elastic beanstalk, route 53, cloudfront, API gateway, etc.  Cloudflare simplifies all of this.

I actually spoke to Mathew Prince on LI and said he's going to smoke ZScaler and he said actually they see themselves disrupting Cisco... Cisco is done IMO.  Really they are the new infrastructure of the enterprise for b2b and b2c.  

What would be really freaking cool is if they merged with SHOP.

author: deepee20
body:
I wasn't old enough to be investing during the dotcom burst, but like you I've read a lot about that time (and previous bubbles) and agree with your take on the current market.

I wouldn't sell out completely because nobody can know when this will pop, but I've definitely moved to a larger cash position, and avoiding tech and clean energy for now.

You see the denial and 'this time it's different' in every reddit thread about this topic. Those people are invested in incredibly overvalued companies and will do all sorts of mental gymnastics to justify it (as you pointed out, 'Tesla is not a car company').

The obvious point of 'low interest rates, therefore not a bubble' doesn't hold much water since interest rates were trending down in the period before the dotcom burst. The entire last decade saw interest rates lower than that period, yet no-one (except a few perma-bears) pointed to 2014 or 2016 etc. as being in a euphoric bubble.

The other disingenuous point reddit likes to make is that 2000 was full of unprofitable internet startups which can't be compared to the FAANGs of today. Microsoft, Cisco, Intel were the profitable juggernaughts of the time and they also took many years to recover. But just take a look around today (I'll just pick out some random stocks):

* HYLN - no revenues from their main product for at least 1-2 years. 3.2B market cap
* NKLA - Exposed as a fraud last year. 8.4B market cap based on some nice photoshop renders.
* PLUG - no profits. 31.7B market cap (because clean energy hype!)
* TLRY - no profits. 4.6B market cap (because weed legalisation hype!)
* RIDE - no upcoming revenue for the next quarter. 4.4B market cap (ev hype!)
* UBER - no profits, and no demonstration that their business model could ever turn a profit. 112B market cap
* PLTR - no history of profits. 5 months on the market, 55.6B market cap.

I could go on all day, and this is without mentioning the elephants in the room like Tesla. The Pets.com's (and their valuation excuses) are everywhere today, as is the euphoric behaviour.

author: bosshax
body:
Good luck! History does not necessarily repeat in the same way. There are many winners, many losers. Many from dot com had very viable businesses but the plug was pulled. It’s unlikely investors will be so short sighted in any future contraction.

The only real risk to tech valuations are:
a) can growth continue
b) are they ever going to have positive earnings 

If those turn then there goes the valuation but the company may very well survive until they get another shot, eg BlackBerry... Nokia... Cisco... Xerox... lots of companies that at one point were trading at huge multiples just got checked. 

So, just make sure your entire portfolio isn’t in one of them. You can afford a couple losers, cut your losses and move your capital to a winner. One thing is for sure- tech ain’t leaving. Hyper growth strategies aren’t leaving. Disruptive innovation isn’t changing. You’re going to see many companies with high valuations based on nothing more than momentum and trajectory. This is investing in 2021. If you want to invest like it’s 1999 please buy Walmart. You will probably do fine.

author: Shikadi297
body:
>not a gamble if you do research

I guess horse races aren't gambles then

>crash of March 2020

That was a dip, not a crash. The Fed pumped in money to stop it from being a crash.

Look at 2001, where thousands of reputable companies went bankrupt. Companies like Microsoft took a decade to recover, long holds like GE and CISCO never recovered and it's 20 years later, Tesla is incredibly over-valued and reflects 2001 speculation. The market overall is overvalued, and nobody knows whether or not it's a bubble that's about to pop. Even valuable companies like AMD will drop with the rest of the market if this is anything like 2001. People don't even talk about 2001 that much either, they're always focused on 2008, which was pretty much an aftershock. 

Point is, you can increase your odds and make good bets, but all of it is gambling. Timing the market fails most of the time, and the people who succeed get the attention. Index funds are the safest bet because historically they've always gone up on average, and if they stop going up, that probably means we have bigger problems. But to say doing your research makes it not gambling is like saying being good at poker makes it not gambling

author: mnetoo0
body:
Hi! Thank you for the input. This is what I was looking for. 

These were more initial thoughts, not anything set in stone.

Interesting point about QA team. How do you know that, does somebody you know work there?

Absolutely, I'm sure Jayshree Ullal helped a lot if not just in terms of credibility and, as you said, long relationships with customers.

It wasn't supposed to come through as their software being revolutionary. Just that it was actually purpose built for today's environment instead of Cisco's software which has been adapted to fit today's needs - and even their modular software has many, many more CVEs than Arista's.

You mentioned the threats and their intial idea. I can't remember where I saw this but I thought the initial idea was actually prompted by Google. Because from what I know Google put out an RFI in 2004 saying "We're looking for a switch design that can tie together 100,000 servers, each at 1GB, at a cost of $100 a server." One of the questions I had was why Google isn't on of their customers now? They obviously built something in-house. The RFI was in 2004 and Arista only released their first product in 2008.

One of the other questions I had was exactly what you mention. To what extent does the fact that Arista have way less bugs compensate from the fact that they have less features? And in what ways is Cisco's software better? As an example: I was speaking to someone in the photography/marketing business and he was saying photoshop has loads of features but it was built a long time ago. So it's complicated to use, and it may have more bugs, because you're continually updating an old app and having to install 3rd party add ons. But at what point does the "feature set" overweight the bugs.

Also I'd like to ask if you can shine some light on Arista vs. Cisco's software integration with 3rd party applications?

I've heard that about the culture. But another point I'd probably consider is just that a lot of prospective employees don't see as big of a chance to make a lot of money at Arista with stock options, etc. I think that's also part of the reason why they may not be able to, as you claim, hire from the best colleges.

I can see different angles here. Cisco is the incumbent, they've invested loads of money into this software. It has loads of bugs even though it has features. Which do customers prefer? Customer, at least to some extent, do like Arista because they've taken significant share.

Look forward to reading your thoughts!

author: juniorbuffett
body:
Google RFI was a good info and may have been the trigger for their pivot. I think Google is still their customer. I think MSFT (which was at one point 10% plus of their revenue), Google and FB could be the biggest three customers.

Good question about the features vs bugs tradeoff. Arista code quality is hands down much better than Cisco's. Plus Arista has a very competent TAC team which Cisco used to have few decades back. Cloud titans kind of run the same kind of network - mostly IP network with L3 ECMP so they are well satisfied by EOS. Only the service providers might demand more scale which in my opinion EOS lacks. I think my earlier comment might be too harsh on Arista and what they have achieved has been extraordinary. My only concern was not to price in the spectacular past growth, your buy at 200$ gives you a good margin of safety in my opinion.

I think being relatively smaller company Arista can have faster integration with 3rd party apps but overall both should be at the same level. Cisco has for the past decade has lost its edge and missed the bus in terms of cloud, data centre, merchant sillicon adoption. I think it's like IBM now just doing financial engineering and frequent layoffs. It did a "spin-in" of Insieme Networks which was internally codenamed Arista killer but it could not make an impact.  Just to give an example - Cisco  has multiple BUs (Business Units) say service provider, data centre, enterprise -- all with different product lines like Catalyst switches, Nexus switches, IOS-XR routes etc. There is cut-throat competition between these BU sales teams plus lack of sharing of ideas between engineering teams. Compared to this Arista has no BU concept. It's a single engineering, sales team.

I think customers  definitely prefer Arista to Cisco if their use case/requirements are met. Good luck.

author: jpbenz
body:
I won't argue with you about any of the charging companies, because I agree with the long-term value of those products.  

Are you seriously comparing Tesla to Cisco?  When was the last time you heard anyone excited about a network router or a great VOIP product?  Cisco is a great company that probably doesn't get the credit it deserves, but no one is going to be excited by their products and their market demand has been filled.  

The EV market is huge and the demand is just beginning.  Are companies going to be over valued?  Sure, but that value won't be understood until the market demand is met and they are no longer growth companies, but companies that have met the growth demand and are meeting the annual turnover needs of the market.

author: RecommendationNo6304
body:
Check out Gorilla Game  (Moore). It's old, 97, but still very relevant to emerging technologies and disruptive innovations. It gives a lot of good structure towards figuring out where in the lifecycle a new industry might be, which are the top players, whether it's likely to be a monopoly, oligopoly, or something less dominant, and a reasonable approach to invest complete with some case studies (Cisco is among them).

Doing that sort of thing requires you have some deep background into the technology, or a willingness to learn, read lots of trade journals, etc.

Helped me a lot in my thinking about evaluating franchises.

author: CadperGN
body:
Thanks for this addition.

I guess the buzzword for vendor is depending on where you look as all I hear is that the management interface and the distribution of ruleset is so much better on the Check Point gear. That said Check Point is not only a firewall. It's an IPS blade with a firewall. Something (some of) the others charge extra for.

The sentiment for "all cloud" is not my thing. I don't believe in cloud-only for a cross-sector and industry as the replacement for on-prem. Cloud may work on a broad scale for some industries and sectors but I recon we'll see more agnostic and hybrid environments being the norm when we're done buzzwording (as if that ever happens in infosec lol). At some point in time regulation may follow but some things simply don't work well in the cloud (legislation and other outside factors).

About IaC, I see Check Point being much more on-par than for example Cisco. I haven't worked with Fortinet or Palo Alto although we had a sales meeting with Palo Alto for some of the "Next Gen Slideware" they had which I (personal preference) did not like at all. I really do believe that the government wide investment into Cyber Security that Isreal has made will benefit the vendors from there. Cyberark may also be one to benefit although they are far to expensive for my liking atm.

About Fortinet. I haven't had time to proper dig into them yet but the fundamentals python code I've got really have them as a candidate for a rocket in price.

I'm glad to see a fellow Security-person here :-)

author: Wkingwest
body: Nokia has:  Positives -  No debt 90,000+ employees 5G contracts in EU Has a lead on 6G R&D in EU Makes chipsets for most major brand networking switches (Cisco) Retains 20K patents on various telco technologies Has won a $14 million contract with NASA to set up communications infrastructure in the moon (who knows where this could lead if successful - beyond the MOON?) In 1964, their research department discovered cosmic microwave background radiation - they have the resources to discover other interesting endeavors They are transparent in their business dealings, partnerships, and current/upcoming projects, they will also start releasing quarterly financial reports as well Outside of China, they own 27% of the world's telco infrastructure Moving to cloud services like storage and software (SaaS) Internet of Things in the Healthcare industry My 3310 from the year 2000 is still running and has not needed to be plugged in to charge yet  Negatives -  They have lost out on their contract with the 5G rollout in China. They were only involved in phase one, but did not win a tender to participate in phase two. Only Ericsson and Huawei won that round  I think it is a decent long term stock. And at $4.7 - $5 a stock, it is nothing to lose sleep over. They are not gonna go out of business, and you are not going to get wiped out. If it can only go up, then that's a good thing, short term or long term.**Show less**

author: graiz
body:
I've been long on NET since it's IPO and have been a customer of cloudflare for many years before this. 

I'm long for two reasons.   
\#1 - They have the best technology. They focus on low-level network technology like DNS and for years they have had the best technology, best performance and IMO the best price for the value. This makes it a no-brainer for most high-traffic websites.  It's easy to sell the best product and their sales are growing accordingly. 

\#2 - They are constantly innovating.  They keep pushing the state of the art and performance across a number of areas.  CDN, DNS, Smart Routing, Analytics, etc. These products work really well together and they scale with the speed of the Internet. Most people don't know about Cloudflare or their tech so I think they have a ton of room for growth and market expansion. 

Compare NET with older network companies like Cisco, Oracle, EMC, and others.  There's a ton of room for growth and many older companies that don't have the best technology and aren't quick to innovate. 

NET, NET. I like this stock a lot.

author: PoliSciStudent01
body:
Information - 
- 19 years old in the US
- Part-Time working with my University, about $900/mo 
- Brokerage - Build a dividend portfolio to survive (moving to Washington DC in a year for Grad School) Roth - Have a good foundation to grow on
- Brokerage - Around a years time with continued growth. Roth - Not for decades
- Brokerage - Moderate. I'm not opposed to some risk if it helps with growth. Roth - Moderate-High. I won't be touching this for decades
- Current holdings are at the bottom
- No debts
- I'm in my last year of Undergrad and trying to find jobs that I can do while in DC

I'm going to apologize in advance if this post is long/rambling. I'm just at a point of confusion and I'm not sure where to go with my investing and how to optimize it. I don't have enough money for a financial advisor to even notice me, so I figure that y'all are the best source of advice.

I'm a relatively young investor (19 and have been investing for a few months) that's currently working on building up a dividend portfolio with the goal of being able to have a good steady cashflow. I've been following Joseph Hogue's weekly dividend portfolio with the goal of emulating that for my brokerage account. My Roth follows David Swensen's model that he used to build Yale's endowment. I've been able to put $500/mo into my Brokerage and, once I hit at least 1 of each stock from that portfolio (will be able to by the end of February), I plan to split that more evenly across my Roth and my Brokerage. 

I'm planning on shutting down my Robinhood once my cash settles and move the money that I was able to make from GameStop (please don't crucify me lol) into Fidelity.

My main question is how can I optimize my accounts? I like being able to get dividends frequently, but I think getting more dividend income is more important than the frequency. As for my Roth, is there any way that I can improve it? Additionally, what would be the best use of my profits from GameStop investment wise? (About $600). I'd appreciate any and all help/advice :)

author: derek
body:
>  The growth/adoption of their products into the enterprise demonstrate that the company continues to gain traction against the likes of Cisco (CSCO).

Ubiquiti and Cisco are so far apart on the spectrum, this is honestly a bit laughable; Ubiquiti is small business at worst, fortune 5000 at best.

Crazier things have happened, but I don't ever see a time when UBNT gear makes its way into *truly* enterprise environments... a totally different world with very stringent requirements for compliance, uptime, security, and other metrics.

*Source: Sr Network Engineer and user of Ubiquiti gear in my home/lab.*

author: rakkki
body:
I can share what I follow and learned after making so many mistakes. I used to trade weeklies but burned many times due averaging or trade going to opposite direction. So, after losing 50% of portfolio then I stopped the weeklies.
Now, I only trade in growth companies after reseraching. I follow four rules mostly:

1. High growth companies (usually have high IV as well) - I have leaps for PLTR, NIO, XPEV,SKLZ, SQ, MVIS, ABNB etc.( had DKNG, SE,RIOT and JMIA but sold too early yet made goos money)

2. ER corrected companies- I buy leaps for those companies which have good performance but got corrected. Like EHTH, QCOM,AMD, CRM,U,UNH, ANTM, ENPH.

3. Companies which have been consolidation phase- NVDA, CRM since,  I can't time them well so I buy longer period calls and IV is relatively low so they price not that bad for me.

4. Upcoming trends: like currently semi conductors shortages so i bought TSM, TER, AMD, QCOM and NVDA are also in that sector. author: ljr55555
body: I love ENPH. I'd bought their stock when it was around two bucks and am still holding it. My investment didn't have anything to do with financial analysis -- I like their product. In researching to install solar at the house, one of the big problems with solar arrays (when you don't live in a flat, open area) is that production is drops to the level of the lowest producing panel in the array. That big tree at the corner of my property starts throwing some shade on the array, all of those panels in full sun are slacking. Enphase makes "micro-inverters" which allow each panel to operate independently. Their product makes the solar installation a little more expensive on a per-panel basis. In non-ideal solar areas (like where I live), though, the price per kWh produced is better -- or, more accurately, I can produce the power I need with fewer panels (less space AND less money). I expect additional federal incentives either this year or next, so anticipate an increase in residential solar installations. And I'm hoping growth in residential solar installations in places that aren't wide open, flat, super sunny locations drive micro-inverter sales.

author: Optimal_Challenge_92
body:
Y'all need to do some more DD here. TSLA is producing a string inverter - this is not module level power electronics - totally different animal and old tech. Enph has patented all the magic tricks that makes their micros tick and they are coming after commercial installs next (iq8D). Their brain trust is grade A and is continually iterating and improving.  Also, SPWR owns a large chunk of ENPH shares still as part of an agreement when ENPH was restructuring. SPWR makes panels with ENPH micros built in - ENPH is the provider for these. So don't be surprised if good earnings for ENPH reflects in upward momentum for SPWR and vice versa.  Also of note - SI on SPWR is enormous right now. If the market likes this quarter it's not gonna be pretty for the bears. 

Source: I yolo'd approx 50k on ENPH about 2 years ago because I understood the tech (BSEE) and it's still my biggest position. The ENPH management team is LASER FOCUSED.

author: scatterbraimedddd
body: This is where specific watchlists become useful most. It becomes easier to identify and follow trends. If I click on EV and 11 of 15 tickers are green, it's a hot day -I will look for a day trade. Then it happens the next day, "noice", another day trade! At this point EV feels hot. Now review all your lists, maybe after market close, but look for categories that are mostly red. Thats how you ID hot and cold sectors. As for finding undervalued companies, that's the part that involves homework. I will often identify a handful of worst performers, try to see if it's based on news, poor earnings, poor sentiment, etc. Go through the financials. Learning about balance sheets is key here, and its not very hard... Not as fun, but if you ID a good company thats undervalued, it will pay to buy and hold. For me this was ENPH in 2019, I made a killing on it. Also found SI in 2019, that was another gold mine.
